   2891          /******** THE REST OF THE FILE IS DOCUMENTATION ONLY !**********************//**
   2892           * @addtogroup uartdrv UARTDRV - UART Driver
   2893           * @brief Universal Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter Driver
   2894           * @{
   2895          
   2896             @details
   2897             The source files for the UART driver library, uartdrv.c and uartdrv.h, are in the
   2898             emdrv/uartdrv folder.
   2899          
   2900             @n @section uartdrv_intro Introduction
   2901             The UART driver supports the UART capabilities of the USART, UART, and LEUART
   2902             peripherals. The driver is fully reentrant and supports multiple driver instances.
   2903             The driver does not buffer or queue data. However, it queues UART transmit
   2904             and receive operations. Both blocking and non-blocking transfer functions are
   2905             available. Non-blocking transfer functions report transfer completion with
   2906             callback functions. Transfers are done using DMA. Simple direct/forced
   2907             transmit and receive functions are also available. Note that these functions
   2908             are blocking and not suitable for low energy applications because they use CPU
   2909             polling.
   2910          
   2911             UART hardware flow control (CTS/RTS) is fully supported by the driver. UART
   2912             software flow control (XON/XOFF) is partially supported by the driver. For
   2913             more information about flow control support, see @ref uartdrv_fc.
   2914          
   2915             @note Transfer completion callback functions are called from within the DMA
   2916             interrupt handler with interrupts disabled.
   2917          
   2918             @n @section uartdrv_conf Configuration Options
   2919          
   2920             Some properties of the UARTDRV driver are compile-time configurable. These
   2921             properties are set in a uartdrv_config.h file. A template for this
   2922             file, containing default values, is in the emdrv/config folder.
   2923             To configure UARTDRV for your application, provide a custom configuration file,
   2924             or override the defines on the compiler command line.
   2925             These are the available configuration parameters with default values defined.
   2926             @code
   2927          
   2928             // Set to 1 to enable hardware flow control.
   2929           #define EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE       1
   2930          
   2931             // Maximum number of driver instances.
   2932           #define EMDRV_UARTDRV_MAX_DRIVER_INSTANCES      4
   2933          
   2934             // UART software flow control code: request peer to start Tx.
   2935           #define UARTDRV_FC_SW_XON                       0x11
   2936          
   2937             // UART software flow control code: request peer to stop Tx.
   2938           #define UARTDRV_FC_SW_XOFF                      0x13
   2939             @endcode
   2940          
   2941             The properties of each UART driver instance are set at run-time via the
   2942             @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t data structure input parameter to the @ref UARTDRV_InitUart()
   2943             function for UART and USART peripherals, and the @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart_t
   2944             data structure input parameter to the @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart() function for
   2945             LEUART peripherals.
   2946          
   2947             @n @section uartdrv_api The API
   2948          
   2949             This section contains brief descriptions of the functions in the API. For more
   2950             information on input and output parameters and return values,
   2951             click on the hyperlinked function names. Most functions return an error
   2952             code, @ref ECODE_EMDRV_UARTDRV_OK is returned on success,
   2953             see ecode.h and uartdrv.h for other error codes.
   2954          
   2955             The application code must include @em uartdrv.h header file.
   2956          
   2957             @ref UARTDRV_InitUart(), @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart() and @ref UARTDRV_DeInit() @n
   2958              These functions initialize and deinitialize the UARTDRV driver. Typically,
   2959              UARTDRV_InitUart() (for UART/USART) or
   2960              UARTDRV_InitLeuart() (for LEUART) are called once in
   2961              the startup code.
   2962          
   2963             @ref UARTDRV_GetReceiveStatus() and @ref UARTDRV_GetTransmitStatus() @n
   2964              Query the status of a current transmit or receive operations. Reports number
   2965              of items (frames) transmitted and remaining.
   2966          
   2967             @ref UARTDRV_GetReceiveDepth() and  @ref UARTDRV_GetTransmitDepth() @n
   2968              Get the number of queued receive or transmit operations.
   2969          
   2970             @ref UARTDRV_Transmit(), UARTDRV_Receive() @n
   2971             UARTDRV_TransmitB(), UARTDRV_ReceiveB() @n
   2972             UARTDRV_ForceTransmit() and UARTDRV_ForceReceive() @n
   2973              Blocking and non-blocking transfer functions are included.
   2974              The blocking versions have an uppercase B (for Blocking) at the end of
   2975              their function name. Blocking functions do not return before the transfer
   2976              is complete. The non-blocking functions signal a transfer completion with a
   2977              callback function. @ref UARTDRV_ForceTransmit() and
   2978              @ref UARTDRV_ForceReceive() are also blocking. These two functions access
   2979              the UART peripheral directly without using DMA or interrupts.
   2980              @ref UARTDRV_ForceTransmit() does not respect flow control.
   2981              @ref UARTDRV_ForceReceive() forces RTS low.
   2982          
   2983             @ref UARTDRV_Abort() @n
   2984              Abort current transmit or receive operations and remove all queued
   2985              operations.
   2986          
   2987             @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSet(), @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlGetSelfStatus(), @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSetPeerStatus() and @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlGetPeerStatus() @n
   2988              Set and get flow control status of self or peer device. Note that the return
   2989              value from these two functions depends on the flow control mode set by
   2990              @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSet(), @ref UARTDRV_InitUart(), or
   2991              @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart().
   2992          
   2993             @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlIgnoreRestrain() @n
   2994              Enables transmission when restrained by flow control.
   2995          
   2996             @ref UARTDRV_PauseTransmit() and @ref UARTDRV_ResumeTransmit() @n
   2997              Pause a currently active transmit operation by preventing the DMA from loading
   2998              the UART FIFO. Will not override HW flow control state (if applicable), but
   2999              can be used in conjunction.
   3000          
   3001             @n @section uartdrv_fc Flow Control Support
   3002          
   3003             If UART flow control is not required, make sure that
   3004             EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE is set to 0. This reduces the code size
   3005             and complexity of the driver.
   3006          
   3007             Both hardware and software flow control are supported. To
   3008             enable either of these, set EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE to 1 in
   3009             uartdrv_config.h.
   3010          
   3011             @n @subsection uartdrv_fc_hw Hardware Flow Control
   3012          
   3013             UART hardware flow control uses two additional pins for flow control
   3014             handshaking, the clear-to-send (CTS) and ready-to-send (RTS) pins.
   3015             RTS is an output and CTS is an input. These are active-low signals.
   3016             When CTS is high, the UART transmitter should stop sending frames.
   3017             A receiver should set RTS high when it is no longer capable of
   3018             receiving data.
   3019          
   3020             @par Peripheral Hardware Flow Control
   3021          
   3022             Newer devices natively support CTS/RTS in
   3023             the USART peripheral hardware. To enable hardware flow control, perform the
   3024             following steps:
   3025          
   3026             - Set EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE to 1.
   3027             - In the @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t struct passed to @ref UARTDRV_InitUart(), set
   3028              @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t.fcType = uartdrvFlowControlHwUart.
   3029             - Define the pins for CTS and RTS by setting ctsPort, ctsPin, rtsPort
   3030              and rtsPin in the init struct.
   3031             - Also define the CTS and RTS locations by setting portLocationCts and
   3032              portLocationRts in the init struct.
   3033          
   3034             @par GPIO Hardware Flow Control
   3035          
   3036             To support hardware flow control on devices that don't have UART CTS/RTS
   3037             hardware support, the driver includes the sl_gpio driver to emulate a
   3038             hardware implementation of UART CTS/RTS flow control on these devices.
   3039          
   3040             To enable hardware flow control, perform the following steps:
   3041          
   3042             - Set EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE to 1.
   3043             - UART/USART: In the @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t struct passed to
   3044              @ref UARTDRV_InitUart(), set
   3045              @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t.fcType = uartdrvFlowControlHw.
   3046             - LEUART: In the @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart_t struct passed to
   3047              @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart(), set
   3048              @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart_t.fcType = uartdrvFlowControlHw.
   3049             - Define the pins for CTS and RTS by setting ctsPort, ctsPin, rtsPort and
   3050              rtsPin in the same init struct.
   3051          
   3052             @note Because of the limitations in GPIO interrupt hardware, you cannot select
   3053             CTS pins in multiple driver instances with the same pin number. For example, pin A0 and
   3054             B0 cannot serve as CTS pins in two concurrent driver instances.
   3055          
   3056             RTS is set high whenever there are no Rx operations queued. The UART
   3057             transmitter is halted when the CTS pin goes high. The transmitter completes
   3058             the current frame before halting. DMA transfers are also halted.
   3059          
   3060             @n @subsection uartdrv_fc_sw Software Flow Control
   3061          
   3062             UART software flow control uses in-band signaling, meaning the receiver sends
   3063             special flow control characters to the transmitter and thereby removes
   3064             the need for dedicated wires for flow control. The two symbols
   3065             UARTDRV_FC_SW_XON and UARTDRV_FC_SW_XOFF are defined in uartdrv_config.h.
   3066          
   3067             To enable support for software flow control, perform the following steps:
   3068          
   3069             - Set EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE to 1.
   3070             - UART/USART: In the @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t structure passed to
   3071              @ref UARTDRV_InitUart(), set
   3072              @ref UARTDRV_InitUart_t.fcType = uartdrvFlowControlSw.
   3073             - LEUART: In the @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart_t structure passed to
   3074              @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart(), set
   3075              @ref UARTDRV_InitLeuart_t.fcType = uartdrvFlowControlSw.
   3076          
   3077             @note Software flow control is partial only.
   3078          
   3079             The application must monitor buffers and make decisions on when to send XON/
   3080             XOFF. XON/XOFF can be sent to the peer using @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSet().
   3081             Though @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSet() will pause the active transmit operation
   3082             to send a flow control character, there is no way to guarantee the order.
   3083             If the application implements a specific packet format where the flow control
   3084             codes may appear only in fixed positions, the application should not
   3085             use @ref UARTDRV_FlowControlSet() but implement read and write of XON/XOFF
   3086             into packet buffers. If the application code fully implements all the flow
   3087             control logic, EMDRV_UARTDRV_FLOW_CONTROL_ENABLE should be set to 0
   3088             to reduce code space.
   3089          
   3090             @n @section uartdrv_example Example
   3091             @if DOXYDOC_P1_DEVICE
   3092              @if DOXYDOC_EFM32G
   3093              @include uartdrv_example_p1_nomvdis.c
   3094              @endif
   3095              @if DOXYDOC_EZR32HG
   3096              @include uartdrv_example_p1_usart0.c
   3097              @endif
   3098              @ifnot (DOXYDOC_EFM32G || DOXYDOC_EZR32HG)
   3099              @include uartdrv_example_p1.c
   3100              @endif
   3101             @endif
   3102             @if DOXYDOC_P2_DEVICE
   3103             @include uartdrv_example_p2.c
   3104             @endif
   3105             @if DOXYDOC_S2_DEVICE
   3106             @include uartdrv_example_s2.c
   3107             @endif
   3108          
   3109           * @} end group uartdrv *********************************************************/

